'''"No More Good Days"''' is the [[series premiere]] of the American television series ''[[FlashForward]]''. The episode's teleplay was written by [[David S. Goyer]] and [[Brannon Braga]], who also conceived of the television story, based upon the [[Flashforward (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Robert J. Sawyer]]. Goyer also directed the episode, which originally aired in the United States on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on September 24, 2009.

The series opens on a seemingly ordinary day on October 6, 2009, that soon becomes extraordinary as everyone in [[Los Angeles]] blacks out for 2 minutes and 17 seconds. It soon becomes apparent the  blackouts occurred worldwide, and were accompanied by a flash-forward where each person saw what might be his or her life on April 29, 2010, about six months in the future. [[FBI Agent]] [[Mark Benford]] and a team of agents in Los Angeles begin gathering clues as to what might have happened as they struggle to come to terms with their own visions, or lack thereof. Meanwhile, Mark's wife and daughter each have disturbing visions of the future with which they must cope. As the episode closes, FBI Agent [[Janis_Hawk#Main_characters|Janis Hawk]] makes a startling discovery: an image from CCTV in Detroit of a man in black, walking through the stadium while everyone around him is unconscious.

==Plot overview==
The episode opens with a car crash. [[Mark Benford]] ([[Joseph Fiennes]]) climbs out of his wrecked car and looks around him: there is devastation everywhere, people lie injured and/or dead in the road, cars and trucks are piled up and things are on fire. Mark calls out for his partner, [[Demetri Noh]] ([[John Cho]]).

In a flashback sequence, each of the leads goes about their daily lives. [[Olivia Benford]] ([[Sonya Walger]]) scrubs up at the hospital before surgery; [[Bryce Varley]] ([[Zachary Knighton]]) prepares to commit suicide by shooting himself at the beach; [[Aaron Stark]] ([[Br<U+00ED>an F. O'Byrne]]) and Mark attend an Alcoholics Anonymous meeting; [[Nicole Kirby]] ([[Peyton List]]) sneaks a boy into the Benford's house as she babysits their daughter [[Charlie Benford|Charlie]] (Lennon Wynn). Later, Mark and his FBI partner Demetri give chase on a freeway after getting a lead on a case. Then, the blackout occurs. Upon awakening, Bryce finds himself alive and helps to save the lives of surfers lost at sea; Olivia's patient flatlines in theatre; Aaron wakes up injured on an electricity pole; Nicole and her boyfriend are in a naked and confused state. Each of them panics and tries to get help.

Everyone slowly admits they experienced a 'vision' during the blackout: Mark was furiously working an FBI case and has resumed drinking alcohol; Olivia was with another man; Janis was 17 weeks pregnant. The Benford's daughter Charlie tells Nicole, "I had a bad dream. I dreamt there were no more good days." World news shows that the blackout was global. Demetri starts to panic when he realises he may be the only person not to experience a flash forward - believing that he will be dead in six months.

Olivia treats an 8-year-old boy, a victim of the blackout. She tells him he will be okay, and he refers to her by name, even though she does not know him. Later, Olivia sobs and tells Mark about her blackout. Her flash forward is shown, in which she is with a man she doesn't recognise. At the hospital (in the present time), that same man from Olivia's vision walks into the ward where the 8-year-old boy resides and asks to speak to Dr Benford.

At the end of the episode, Charlie gives Mark a bracelet she made for him. Mark is alarmed: the bracelet is the same one he saw in his flash forward, indicating that the visions may be coming true. Elsewhere, [[Janis Hawk]] ([[Christine Woods]]) is checking CCTV from during the blackout. She focuses on a baseball game in Detroit and notices that as everyone blacks out, one dark figure is moving across the back of the stadium.

==Title sequence image==
Within the show's logo in this episode is a [[friendship bracelet]] in the hand of Charlie Benford when she gives it to her father, Mark.

==Production==
===Development===
[[File:Brannon braga.jpg|thumb|right|Producer [[Brannon Braga]] was the co-writer and executive producer for the first three episodes of the series.]]
The series was conceived by [[David S. Goyer]] and [[Brannon Braga]], based upon the [[Flashforward (novel)|novel of the same name]]. The two had previously worked together on the short-lived [[CBS]] series ''[[Threshold (TV series)|Threshold]]'' The idea was originally pitched to [[HBO]], a pay-cable network, however the HBO leadership felt that the series was better suited to a broadcast network. With the consent of HBO, Goyer and Braga pitched the idea to both ABC and [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]], with ABC winning the bidding war. In the early stages of development, ABC considered coupling the new show with ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airlockalpha.com/node/5390 |title=Brannon Braga Working Again With David Goyer On ''Flash Forward'' |publisher=[[Airlock Alpha]] | author=Hinman, Michael |accessdate=October 28, 2009 | date=September 21, 2008}}</ref> This created a problem, as Braga was an [[executive producer]] of the Fox series ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]''. ABC Studios
and [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] discussed co-producing ''FlashForward'', but Braga eventually pulled out of his "day-to-day" involvement with the project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i47f5cb6394a9cc0f850c2467680734c8 |title=ABC sees the future, buys it |publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | first=Nellie |accessdate=January 29, 2010 | last=Andreeva| date=September 19, 2008|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5n9LVXyQS |archivedate=January 29, 2010}}</ref>

When writing the script, one of the most "obvious" changes from the novel was altering how far into the future the characters see when they black out. from "21 years to six months", according to [[Marc Guggenheim]]. Guggenheim felt that the "real appeal" of the series is "getting to see the payoff of when the future becomes the present", and Goyer and Braga made the decision to create a first season "payoff" early in the writing process.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/tvnews.php?id=56675 |title=Marc Guggenheim Talks ''Flash Forward'' |publisher=[[CraveOnline|CoomingSoon.net]]| author= |accessdate=October 28, 2009 | date=June 27, 2009}}</ref> Another difference is the characters of [[FBI Special Agent]]s [[Mark Benford]] and [[Demetri Noh]], neither of whom appears in the book. The main character in the book is Lloyd Simcoe, the scientist who created the flash-forward.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvovermind.com/featured/from-book-to-tv-can-flash-forward-work/6688 |title=From Book to TV: Can ''Flash Forward'' Work? |publisher=[[CraveOnline|TV Overmind]] | author=McPherson, Sam | accessdate=October 28, 2009 | date=July 20, 2009}}</ref>

===Casting===
On May 8, 2009 it was announced that ''FlashForward'' was to comprise part of ABC's fall 2009 season. Prior to this, the network had aired several five second advertisements featuring plot elements and characters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/11/arts/television/11arts-ABCTOFLASHFO_BRF.html |title=ABC to ''Flash Forward'' |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | author=Stelter, Brian |accessdate=October 28, 2009 | date=May 10, 2009}}</ref> [[Courtney B. Vance]] and [[Jack Davenport]] became the first officially announced cast members of ''FlashForward''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE4B11JX20081202 |title=Vance, Davenport ''Flash Forward'' to sci-fi pilot |publisher=''[[Reuters]]''| author=Andreeva, Nellie |accessdate=October 28, 2009 | date=December 8, 2008 }}</ref> On June 10, 2009, it was announced that ''Lost'' star [[Dominic Monaghan]] had been cast in the series although his role was then unknown.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory?id=8169329 |title=Dominic Monaghan Joining Cast of ''FlashForward'' |publisher=[[ABC News]] | date=July 24, 2009 | author=|accessdate=October 28, 2009 | date=September 19, 2008}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Rumors of Monaghan's casting began after an advert of him being asked by ''[[Friends]]'' actress [[Courteney Cox]] "What did you see?" was aired as part of the ABC House advertising campaign. It was not immediately revealed which TV series Monaghan would be starring in, but it was eventually announced that he was joining the cast of ''FlashForward''.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.movieline.com/2009/10/dominic-monaghan-on-joining-flashforward-and-his-traumatic-end-on-lost.php |title=Dominic Monaghan On Joining FlashForward and His 'Traumatic' End On Lost |first=Kyle |last=Buchanan |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5n9MWzigL |accessdate=January 29, 2010 |archivedate=January 29, 2010|date=October 1, 2009 |publisher=MovieLine.com}}</ref> On December 5, 2008, it was reported
that Fiennes and Cho had been added to the cast,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/a137573/fiennes-to-lead-flash-forward-pilot.html |title=Fiennes to lead ''Flash Forward'' pilot |publisher=[[Digital Spy]]| author=Reynolds, Simon |accessdate=October 28, 2009 | date=December 5, 2008}}</ref>  followed by the announcement that [[Sonya Walger]] and [[Christine Woods]] had also been cast.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/a137997/flash-forward-cast-adds-two-more.html |title=''Flash Forward'' cast adds two more |publisher=Digital Spy| author=Reynolds, Simon |accessdate=October 28, 2009 | date=December 10, 2008}}</ref> Sonya, who is British, uses an American accent in the show for her part as Olivia. In an interview with [[Digital Spy]], Walger described Olivia as the "main woman in the show".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/cult/a178049/sonya-walger-flashforward.html |title=Sonya Walger (''FlashForward'') |publisher=Digital Spy| author=French, Dan
|accessdate=October 28, 2009 | date=September 21, 2009}}</ref> [[Gabrielle Union]] was announced to be playing the part of Zoey on July 30, 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/a168131/gabrielle-union-joins-flashforward.html |title=Gabrielle Union joins ''FlashForward'' |publisher=Digital Spy| author=Parks, Tim |accessdate=October 28, 2009 | date=July 30, 2009}}</ref> and [[Seth MacFarlane]] on June 18, 2009 as  FBI agent Jake Curdy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/cult/a160763/macfarlane-to-recur-on-flashforward.html |title=MacFarlane to recur on ''FlashForward'' |publisher=Digital Spy| author=French, Dan |accessdate=October 28, 2009 | date=June 18, 2009}}</ref>

== Broadcast and reception ==
=== Ratings and viewership ===
This episode was watched by 12.47 million American viewers, with a 7.7/13 overall [[Nielsen ratings|household rating]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.com/2009/09/25/thursday-broadcast-finals-plus-quarter-hour-detail-for-flashforward/28439|title=TV Ratings: ''FlashForward'' flashes brightly; ''Grey's'' annihilates ''CSI'', ''The Mentalist''|publisher=''TV by the Numbers''|accessdate=October 29, 2009}}</ref> This episode was watched by 4.1 million British viewers on its premiere on [[Five (TV channel)|Five]].
The repeat the following Friday reached 1.28 million. The satellite repeat on [[Fiver (channel)|Fiver]] attracted 601 thousand viewers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barb.co.uk/report/weeklyTopProgrammes/?RequestTimeout=500&report=weeklytop30 |title=BARB's multichannel top 10 programmes w/e 4 Oct 2009 (scroll down to Five) |publisher=barb.co.uk |accessdate=October 29, 2009}}</ref> [[CTV Television Network|CTV]] bought the rights for the series in May, 2009, though it was not known at that time what channel it would air at on the CTV television network.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118004131.html?categoryid=19&cs=1 |title=CTV nabs ''Flash Forward'' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | author=Levine, Stuart |accessdate=October 28, 2009 | date=May 23, 2009}}</ref>

