=== Critical reception ===
{{Quote box | quote="Whatever the outcome, be it a solar flare, God punishing the world, or an angry Minnesota Twins fan, the interplay between fate and freewill fuels the drama more than the mystery itself. If ''FlashForward'' can keep the momentum it set in its premiere episode, the show's apocalyptic tone and fate-bending intrigue should prove deeply fascinating". | source = Kris King of ''[[Slant Magazine|Slant]]''<ref>{{cite news | author=Kris, King | url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/tv/review/flashforward/121 | title=''FlashForward'' | work=[[Slant Magazine|Slant]] | date=September 24, 2009 | accessdate=October 29, 2009}}</ref> | width =250px | align = left }}
Reviews of the premiere were generally positive. According to [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Normalization (statistics)|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the premiere has received a "generally favorable" score of 72, based on 26 reviews.<ref name="Metacritics">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/shows/flashforward?q=flashforward |title=''FlashForward'' |work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=''CNET Networks''|accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref> Gina Bellafante of ''[[The New York Times]]'' found the premiere to work "just as powerfully as a domestic drama as it does as a mechanism of apocalyptic intrigue".<ref>{{cite news | author=Bellafante, Gina | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/24/arts/television/24flash.html?_r=1 | title=Fearing a Future They<U+2019>ve Seen | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=September 23, 2009 | accessdate=October 29, 2009}}</ref> David Zurawik of ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', likewise, said, "It's smart, richly textured, complex and filled with
suspense and intellectual challenge--in short, it has all the things network television is supposed to have abandoned in favor of cheap reality shows."<ref>{{cite news | author=Zurawik, David | url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2009-09-24/entertainment/0909230079_1_benford-noh-serialized-dramas | title=ABC takes a leap of faith in ''FlashForward'' | work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] | date=September 24, 2009| accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref> ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' reviewer Tim Goodman said, "If you like big-screen-level thrills and complicated plot structures, you'll opt-in to ''FlashForward''. And you'll be rewarded. Here's hoping it stays strong and compelling as it heads to April 29."<ref>{{cite news | author=Goodman, Tim | url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2009/09/24/DDPP19R101.DTL&type=movies | title=Tim Goodman: The future looks very promising | work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] | date=September 23, 2009 | accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref> Paige Wiser from the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' was overall positive towards the premiere episode, comparing it to another ABC series, ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]''.<ref name="Metacritics"/> Reviewer Ken Tucker of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' said the premiere combined "sci-fi-ish conspiracy suspense with excellent prime-time-soap drama" giving it a B+.<ref>{{cite news | author=Tucker, Ken | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20314284,00.html| title=''FlashForward'' | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | date=October 20, 2009 | accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref>

Some critics, however, had more mixed feeling towards the [[pilot episode]]. Tom Shales from ''[[The Washington Post]]'' gave a mixed-to-positive review of the episode, saying, "The new series seems to share a perhaps fatal flaw of that now-canceled show [''[[Pushing Daisies]]''], which is that the premise becomes so byzantine and the complications so arcane that eventually people just give up on trying to make sense of the darn thing."<ref>{{cite news | author=Shales, Tom | url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/09/23/AR2009092304324.html | title=ABC's 'Flash': Wrinkles in Space-Time | publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]'' | date=September 24, 2008| accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' writer Robert Lloyd, said it was "a decent but not brilliant beginning".<ref>{{cite news | author=Lloyd, Robert | url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/sep/24/entertainment/et-flash-forward24 | title=''FlashForward'' | publisher=''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' | date=November 24, 2009|
accessdate=October 28, 2009}}</ref> In her review, Ellen Gray of the ''[[Philadelphia Daily News]]'', was not pleased with the outcome, comparing it to the pilot episode of ''Lost'' and commenting that "No More Good Days" felt "more like deja vu, with characters who could've been rounded up from a disaster miniseries".<ref>{{cite news | author=Gray, Ellen | url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/television/20090924_Ellen_Gray__MacFarlane_creations_dominate_Fox_offerings.html | title=Ellen Gray: MacFarlane creations dominate Fox offerings | publisher=''[[Philadelphia Daily News]]'' | date=November 24, 2009| accessdate=October 28, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

==Awards and nominations==
In April 2010, it was nominated for the [[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation, Short Form]].

The episode was nominated for three [[62nd Primetime Emmy Awards|2010 Emmy awards]]: Outstanding Cinematography For A One Hour Series, Outstanding Music Composition For A Series (Original Dramatic Score), and Outstanding Stunt Coordination.<ref>[http://www.emmys.com/sites/emmys.com/files/62ndemmys_noms.pdf Emmy nomination list]</ref>

